Matthew is a prolific writer, editor, and self-described "newsie" who\'s worked in television markets in Oklahoma, California, and Hawaii. MAILI, Hawaii (Island News) -- No injuries have been reported after a fixed-wing aircraft made an emergency landing in Maili, Tuesday morning. The call went out to the Honolulu Fire Department as an “aircraft fire incident” on in the 87-200 block of Farrington Highway around 10:40 a.m. According to HFD, the aircraft made the emergency landing and all passengers escaped without injuries. The plane was a Van\'s RC-12 that sat two people. The plane took off from the Daniel K. Inouye Airport just after 9 a.m. A report from Honolulu Emergency Medical Services (EMS) listed the location of the emergency landing as Lualualei Naval Road. The EMS report listed the incident as a “fixed-wing plane with emergency landing--no injuries noted to passengers.” According to the Pacific Flight Academy, this incident was a "precautionary landing." The aircraft was not damaged and both pilots are safe. The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued the following statement regarding this incident: "A single-engine Vans RV-12 crashed on a highway in Waianae, Oahu, around 10:30 a.m. local time Tuesday, Feb. 6. Two people were on board. The FAA and the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) will investigate. The NTSB will be in charge of the investigation and will provide any updates." This incident remains under investigation. Tap here to look at the aircraft\'s flight path via Flight Aware. Do you have a story idea?
